@Flyman: Don't worry, I know jazz, my dad was a jazz musician by profession for the most of his lifetime.

If you take your time listening to several performances, preferrably with several artists, in the same vein as the Sandell / Grip / Rolfsson above, you will ‚Äì provided you have an open mind ‚Äì notice that it's not just ‚Äúsome random crap anybody can do‚Äù, as you so eloquently put it. It is complex, it has rules, and the musicians do play together to create a piece. It doesn't, however, have many harmonies: it is best characterized by it's atonality.

I'm not saying it's pretty, nor do I expect it to ever become my favourite music category.  After listening to several performances by several artists I do find it very interesting, though, and I'm sure I will visit this kind of music from time to time.

